# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Array is sorted and rotated if we are able to find in which part target is present and also whether it is sorted or not then we can search easily by binary search.

For detailed explanation you can refer to my youtube channel (Hindi Language)
https://youtu.be/hZOtEvTCAvQ
 or link in my profile.Here,you can find any solution in playlists monthwise from june 2023 with detailed explanation.i upload daily leetcode solution video with short and precise explanation (5-10) minutes.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

1. Initialize two pointers `i` and `j` to represent the current search interval, where `i` is the left boundary and `j` is the right boundary.

2. Enter a loop that continues as long as `i` is less than or equal to `j`.

3. Calculate the middle index `mid` as `i + (j - i) / 2`.

4. Check if the element at index `mid` is equal to the target. If it is, return `mid` as the index where the target is found.

5. Check if the left part of the interval (from `i` to `mid`) is sorted:

   a. If `nums[mid] >= nums[i]`, then the left part is sorted.

   b. Check if the target is within the range of values in the left sorted part (`nums[i]` to `nums[mid]`). If yes, update `j = mid - 1` to search in the left part; otherwise, update `i = mid + 1` to search in the right part.

6. Check if the right part of the interval (from `mid` to `j`) is sorted:

   a. If `nums[mid] <= nums[j]`, then the right part is sorted.

   b. Check if the target is within the range of values in the right sorted part (`nums[mid]` to `nums[j]`). If yes, update `i = mid + 1` to search in the right part; otherwise, update `j = mid - 1` to search in the left part.

7. If none of the conditions above is satisfied, return `-1` to indicate that the target element is not found in the array.

8. After the loop ends (when `i > j`), return `-1` to indicate that the target element is not found in the rotated sorted array.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:O(log n)
