Basically - the difference from a noraml Binary Search, is the decision to choose the left side or the right side of the array, other than that is pretty much the same.

As yo probably know, one side has to be in ascendant order, so in order to search on the left side of the array, it has to be in either of those 2 set of conditions:
1. 	The first and last element of the left side array is in asc order AND the target val is in between those first and last values.
1. 	The frist and last element of the right side array is in asc order AND the target val is NOT in between those first and last values.

Otherwise search for the right side of the array

    public int search(int[] nums, int target) {

        int from = 0;
        int to = nums.length -1;

        while(from<=to){

            int mid = from + (to-from)/2;

            if(nums[mid] == target){
                return mid;
            }

            if( isInLeftSide(nums[from], nums[to], nums[mid], target) ){
                to = mid-1;
            }else {
                from = mid+1;
            }
        }

        return -1;
    }

     //Left side is asc order AND is between the target OR  R side is asc order AND is NOT between the target
    private boolean isInLeftSide(int from, int to, int mid, int target){
        return (from <= mid && isBetweenInclusive(target,from,mid)) || (mid <= to && !isBetweenInclusive(target,mid,to));
    }

    private boolean isBetweenInclusive(int target, int from, int to){
        return from <=target && to >= target;
    }

