solutions.content:
The difficulty of applying binary search to this problem lies in how to determine the correct half for `target`. 

When we do binary search, we start wtih a `l` pointer and a `r` pointer. Then we compute the `m` pointer, if `nums[m]` happens to be `target`, then we are of luck. Otherwise, `nums[m]` can be either to the left or right of `target`. If `nums[m]` is to the left of `target`, we search for the right half; otherwise the left half. So we need to figure out how to check whether `nums[m]` is to the left or right of `target`.

When `nums[m]` is to the left of `target`: `nums[l] nums[m] target nums[r]`, we will have three cases:

1. `nums[l] > nums[m] < target`;
2. `nums[l] <= nums[m] > target`;
3. `nums[l] <= nums[m] < target`.

Note that `m` may be just `l` since the division to compute `m` is a floor division.

Similarly, when `nums[m]` is to the right of `target`: `nums[l] target nums[m] nums[r]`, we will have other three cases:

4. `nums[l] > target < nums[m]`;
5. `nums[l] <= target > nums[m]`;
6. `nums[l] <= target < nums[m]`.

You may just code either cases 1, 2, 3 or cases 4, 5, 6 to determine whether to check the left or right half. The code is as follows.

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int search(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        int n = nums.size(), l = 0, r = n - 1;
        while (l <= r) {
            int m = (l + r) / 2;
            if (nums[m] == target) {
                return m;
            }
            if (left(nums[l], nums[m], target)) {
                l = m + 1;
            } else {
                r = m - 1;
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
private:
    bool left(int l, int m, int t) {
        return (l > m && l > t && m < t) || (l <= m && l > t && m > t) || (l <= m && l < t && m < t);
    }
};
```

In general binary search, we will compare `nums[m]` with `target` to determine the half.

When `nums[m] > target`, it corresponds to cases 2, 4, and 6. In case 2, we need to check for the right half while in cases 4 and 6 the left. And cases 4 and 6 can be compressed into `nums[l] <= target || nums[l] > nums[m]`.

Similarly, when `nums[m] < target`, it corresponds to cases 1, 3, and 5. In case 5, we need to check the left while in cases 1 and 3 the right. And cases 1 and 3 can be compressed into `nums[l] > target || nums[l] <= nums[m]`.

Using the above compressed checks, we will come to the following code.

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int search(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        int l = 0, r = nums.size() - 1;
        while (l <= r) {
            int m = (l + r) / 2;
            if (nums[m] == target) {
                return m;
            }
            if (nums[m] > target) {
                if (nums[l] <= target || nums[l] > nums[m]) {
                    r = m - 1;
                } else {
                    l = m + 1;
                }
            } else {
                if (nums[l] > target || nums[l] <= nums[m]) {
                    l = m + 1;
                } else {
                    r = m - 1;
                }
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```

You may wonder, for example, when `nums[m] > target`, why don't we need a check for case 2 before entering `l = m + 1`? Actually, when `nums[l] <= target || nums[l] > nums[m]` does not hold, it is just case 2. Similarly you can explain why we don't need to check for case 5 before entering `r = m - 1` below.

Another simple approach is to use the sorted version of the array by applying some tricks to the indices. It is not easy to search in `4, 5, 6, 7, 0, 1, 2`, but it is very easy to search in `0, 1, 2, 4, 5, 6, 7`. Suppose you would like to visit the `3`-rd element in the sorted array, in this case, it is just the `(3 + 4) % 7 = 0`-th element in the rotated array. The `4` is just the index of the minimum. You can find it out using the same idea of [Find Minimum in Rotated Sorted Array](https://leetcode.com/problems/find-minimum-in-rotated-sorted-array/).

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int search(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        int l = 0, r = nums.size() - 1, idx = findMinIdx(nums);
        while (l <= r) {
            int m = l + (r - l) / 2, mid = (m + idx) % nums.size();
            if (nums[mid] == target) {
                return mid;
            }
            if (nums[mid] < target) {
                l = m + 1;
            } else {
                r = m - 1;
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
private:
    int findMinIdx(vector<int>& nums) {
        int l = 0, r = nums.size() - 1;
        while (l < r && nums[l] > nums[r]) {
            int m = l + (r - l) / 2;
            if (nums[m] > nums[r]) {
                l = m + 1;
            } else {
                r = m;
            }
        }
        return l;
    }
};
```

