solutions.content:
#### The idea
In order to fullfill the condition of a running time of `O(logn)`, we must use the binary search algorithm. However, Binary search algorithm only works if all the element in the array is sorted, when we have a `pivot` or `rotate` point in our array, we will find that the array is splited in to two parts, 1 to the left of the `rotate` point where everything is sorterd, and 1 to the right(included the `rotate` point) where everything is sorted. In order to apply binary search to find our `target`, we need to figure our which part of the sorted array does the `target` belong to, and from there everything is just standard binary search. 

*How can we find which part is it in?*
we can make sure a part of the array is all sorted, if the beginning number is smaller than the end number, other wise, there must be a `rotate` point in between

``` javascript
var search1pass = function(nums, target) {
    if (nums.length == 0) {
        return -1;
    }
    if (nums.length == 1) {
        return nums[0] == target?0:-1;
    }
    let low = 0, high = nums.length - 1;
    while (low <= high) {
        mid = parseInt((low + (high - low)/2))
        if (target == nums[mid]) {
            return mid
        } else if (nums[low] <= nums[mid]) { // this means everything in between `low` & `mid` is in correct order
            // if target is bigger than nums[low] (the smallest # in this partial array) and smaller than nums[mid](the biggest # in this partial array)
            if (target >= nums[low] && target < nums[mid]) { 
                high = mid - 1; // shift the right boundary to left of mid
            } else {
                // otherwise, our target is in the other end, shift the left boundary to right of mid
                low = mid + 1;
            }
        } else { // there must be a rotate point in between `low` and `mid`, and in between `mid` and `high`, the numbers should be in correct order
            // if the target is in between `mid` and `high`
            if (target <= nums[high] && target > nums[mid]) {
                low = mid + 1; // shift the left boundary to the right of mid
            } else {
                high = mid - 1 // shift the right boudary to the left of mid, 
            }
        }
    }
    return -1;
}
```
**I think this version is better since it's more consistent and easier to understand**
