# "Brute force" intuitive Approach O(log(n))

If you were ever stuck on this problem, you might've arrived at this optimal approach if you simply "blindy" drew out the possible cases. As you do so, you will notice that it just consists of a few if-statements and is not difficult too difficult to code up at all. This is the first approach which is still an optimal approach.

However, as you can see from other posts or if you ponder on the problem long enough, the code (shown below) can surely be condensed as there's repetitive logic somewhere in there. But here's a good way to start as it still a **O(log(n))** solution. **I will show you what the non repetitive version is later**.

**Case 1) The Array is Rotated**
* Case 1.1) The MID is in the **LEFT** subarray
	* 1.1.1) The target is between the (MID, LEFT] -> Only look at LEFT of MID -> *R = mid-1*
	* 1.1.2) Else only look at RIGHT of mid -> *L = mid+1*
* Case 1.2) The MID is in the **RIGHT** subarray
	* 1.2.1) The target is between the (MID, RIGHT] -> Only look at RIGHT of mid -> *L = mid+1*
	* 1.2.2) Else only look at LEFT of mid -> *R = mid-1*

**Case 2) The Array is NOT Rotated** (this is the logic that can be removed)
* Case 2.1) Do a regular binary search (you should know this)
	* 2.1) Target is between (MID, RIGHT] --> L = mid+1
	* 2.2) Else --> R = mid-1

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/636b2f48-85c1-4029-8c74-85bb57e692e5_1656176521.2446127.png)


**Code**
```
class Solution {
public:
    int search(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        int L = 0;
        int R = nums.size()-1;
        int mid;
        while(L <= R){
            mid = (L+R)/2;

            // found target
            if(nums[mid] == target)
                return mid;

            // case1: rotated case
            if(nums[L] > nums[R]){

                // case 1.1: mid is in left subarray
                if(nums[mid] >= nums[L]){
                    if(target >= nums[L] && target < nums[mid]) // 1.1.1
                        R = mid-1;
                    else // 1.1.2
                        L = mid+1;

                // case 1.2: mid is in right subarray
                } else {
                    if(target > nums[mid] && target <= nums[R]) // 1.2.1
                        L = mid+1;
                    else // 1.2.2
                        R = mid-1;
                }

            // case2: regular binary search
            } else {
                if(nums[mid] > target)
                    R = mid-1;
                else
                    L = mid+1;
            }
        }

        return -1;
    }
};
```
_________________
# Removed repetitive logic from intuitive Approach O(log(n))

Now if you can notice it, the whole of case 2 where we do a regular binary search is actually not needed. We can compeltely remove case 2 and simply always run case 1. 

Why is this?

Look at Case 1.1. Our code logic for case 1.1 is: `if(nums[mid] >= nums[L])`. In a regular sorted array like [0,1,2,3,4,5], this if statement is always true. Now if we look at Cases 1.1.1 and 1.1.2 that fall under Case 1.1, this is just the same as a regular binary search. 
* Case 1.1.1 says: "If target is between (MID, LEFT] --> Look at LEFT of MID -> R = mid-1, ELSE look at RIGHT of mid ->L = mid+1

This is just another way to write the if statements in a regular binary search!
As a result, we can remove Case 2 entirely and always run Case 1 only. You would've gotten to this solution if you realized that Case 1.1 is not just checking if MID is in the left subarray, but it is actually also checking if MID is in the SORTED portion of the array which is always the input in a regular binary search. 

**Code**
```
class Solution {
public:
    int search(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        int L = 0;
        int R = nums.size()-1;
        int mid;
        // L   R
        while(L <= R){
            mid = (L+R)/2;

            // found target
            if(nums[mid] == target)
                return mid;

            // case 1.1: mid is in left subarray aka the SORTED subarray
            if(nums[mid] >= nums[L]){
                if(target >= nums[L] && target < nums[mid])
                    R = mid-1;
                else
                    L = mid+1;

            // case 1.2: mid is in right subarray
            } else {
                if(target > nums[mid] && target <= nums[R])
                    L = mid+1;
                else
                    R = mid-1;
            }
        }

        return -1;
    }
};
```

