solutions.content:
I have seen a lot of soutions which are over complicated. It's hard to grasp especially for beginners.
Okay, let's get into it
[ 4, 5, 6, 7, 0, 1, 2 ] // sorted but rotated so, we can't apply binary search directly.
- In the array you can see two sorted subarray
- when we find the mid in array, we check if  mid == target if so, we return the mid index.
- else we check left is sorted ( arr[low] <= arr[mid] ) 
	- if left if sorted we check wether target belongs to left half or right half
- if left half is not sorted it gurantees that right half is sorted therefore we check if element belong to right of left half again.

```
class Solution {
public:
    int search(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        int n = nums.size();
        if(n==0)return -1;

        int low =0;
        int high = n-1;
        while(low <= high){
            int mid = low + (high-low)/2;
            if(nums[mid]==target){
                return mid;
            }

            // check if left half is sorted
            if(nums[low] <= nums[mid]){
                if(target>=nums[low] && target<=nums[mid]){ // check if target belongs to left sorted subarray
                    high = mid-1;
                }else{
                    low = mid+1;
                }
            }else{
                // if left is not sorted it gurantees that right half if sorted

                if(target>=nums[mid] && target<=nums[high]){
                    low = mid+1;
                }else{
                    high = mid-1;
                }
            }
        }

        return -1;
    }
};

```

