We made a video to talk about BFS on the high level and how to implement it for Clone Graph: https://youtu.be/98hj6RdBwXg

To solve this problem we need to visit every node in the graph so we can make a deep copy of them and connect them teo each other. Two algorithms that can be used to achieve this is BFS and DFS. For this problem, we'll use BFS.

**High Level Algorithm**
A BFS algorithm requires 2 things:
1) A Queue datastructure to help traverse our node in a BFS order
2) A visited Set to keep track of the nodes that we visited so that we won’t explore them again.

There are 3 steps involved in a BFS (or DFS) algorithm.
1) Put the given starting node in queue and visited set
2) Iterate through the queue until emptied
3) Pop a node from the queue, iterate through its children and add them to the visited set and queue if we haven’t seen them before.

The only adaption that we need to do to solve the problem is that we will create the copy of the node and connect them when we are processing the node in step 3.

**BFS Solution:**
```
class Solution {
    public Node cloneGraph(Node node) {
        if (node == null) {
            return null;
        }
        Queue<Node> queue = new LinkedList();
        Map<Integer, Node> cloneMap = new HashMap();
        queue.add(node);
        cloneMap.put(node.val, new Node(node.val));

        while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
            Node cur = queue.remove();
            Node clone = cloneMap.getOrDefault(cur.val, new Node(cur.val));
            cloneMap.put(cur.val, clone);
            for (Node child : cur.neighbors) {
                Node childClone = cloneMap.getOrDefault(child.val, new Node(child.val));
                clone.neighbors.add(childClone);
                if (!cloneMap.containsKey(child.val)) {
                    queue.add(child);
                }
                cloneMap.put(child.val, childClone);
            }
        }
        return cloneMap.get(node.val);
    }
}
```

